hamptonshire, England"},"nl":{"1569–":"1569–Overleden","1584–1638":"1584–1638","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569–Female":"1569–Overleden","1569":"1569","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1584":"1584","1571":"1571","1638":"1638","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, England"},"en":{"1569–":"1569–Deceased","1584–1638":"1584–1638","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569–Female":"1569–Deceased","1569":"1569","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1584":"1584","1571":"1571","1638":"1638","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Calthorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Calthorpe (Norfolk)."],"variants":[{"name":"Colthorpe","meanings":["English:  see  Calthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Calthorp","meanings":["English:  see  Calthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Calthrop","meanings":["English:  see  Calthorpe  ."]},{"name":"Coathup","meanings":["English: variant of   Calthorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705205,"age":0,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":2,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":31,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":51,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705213,"age":73,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705216,"age":119,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Calthorpe was born in 1569, in Lincolnshire, England. She married Thomas Barron. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1569–":"1569–Surnud","1584–1638":"1584–1638","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569–Female":"1569–Surnud","1569":"1569","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1584":"1584","1571":"1571","1638":"1638","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1569–":"1569–Kuollut","1584–1638":"1584–1638","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569–Female":"1569–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1584":"1584","1571":"1571","1638":"1638","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, England"},"fr":{"1569–":"1569–Décédée","1584–1638":"1584–1638","1600–1620":"1600–1620","1569–Female":"1569–Décédée","1569":"1569","1689":"1689","1600":"1600","1688":"1688","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","1651":"1651","1584":"1584","1571":"1571","1638":"1638","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Welton, Northamptonshire, England":"Welton, Northamptonshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Margaret Calthorpe est née en 1569, à Lincolnshire, Angleterre. Elle a épousé Thomas Barron. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée à Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1569–":"1569–Verstorben","1584–1638":"1584–1638","1600–1620":"1600–1620",